    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDef_2">Exact vs Approximate Values: Some quantities can be measured precisely, but most are approximate. Measurements can be lower (deficit) or higher (excess) than the true value.</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefQuestion_2">Is every real-world measurement exact? (True / False)</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerOne_2">True</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerTwo_2">False</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerThree_2">Neither</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_2">False</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryProperties_2">Properties:\n
◦ Method of Bounds: Unknown values are estimated within lower and upper limits (e.g., 19 &lt; m &lt; 21).\n
◦ Estimating Dependents: Bounds of one variable give bounds for another (if 3 &lt; x &lt; 5, then 1/5 &lt; 1/x &lt; 1/3).\n
◦ Bounds are usually expressed as decimals with small adjustments to maintain accuracy.</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsQuestion_2">If 2 &lt; x &lt; 4, which is the correct bound for 1/x?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerOne_2">1/2 &lt; 1/x &lt; 1/4</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_2">1/4 &lt; 1/x &lt; 1/2</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerThree_2">2 &lt; 1/x &lt; 4</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_2">1/4 &lt; 1/x &lt; 1/2</string>

